Brought my bf here for his birthday. We had 5 courses for $111 per person (wine not included but good thing we aren't drinkers). Any 5 dishes you choose (stack 'em or mix and match choosing from appetizers, main courses and desserts. ALL of the dishes that were served were excellent in flavor and their portion size is great. Perfectly prepared and they have great service. Oh and you HAVE to try their chocolate soufflé. Worth every penny and can't wait to go back.

Tried things I never would order and everything was amazing. The way the chef was able to blend the flavors and ingredients, was art. Will come back every time I'm in SF.

Recently had my third dinner at GD, and was as impressed as ever. Excellent service, professional, attentive, but not snooty. We ordered the five course menu, which is mix and match as you will, and offers an excellent value considering the quality of the food. Absolutely everything we ate was superb, if not quite mind-blowing. You will not find a comparable intersection of fabulous food, prepared and presented beautifully, with such wonderful value in any other high end restaurant in SF. This classic place is a classic for good reason. It deserves to be.

Even in the city like SF where the food business is increasingly competitive, Gary Danko is still one of the best restaurants in SF. What's interesting about Gary Danko is, I can mix and match and create my own tasting menu, whether there are only 3 courses, or 5 courses when I'm starving and want to treat myself as royalty. And you can choose which one as starter or entree as you wish, and the chef will size the portion accordingly. How considerate! Now back to the real business - food. After trying about half of the menu, I would say there are some exceptional dishes that rarely other restaurants are able to deliver, which makes Gary Danko so special. The seafood dishes are far more memorable than meat and poultry dishes, and their dessert... to die for! What I like most: - Risotto with rock shrimp and Dungeness crab*** Love the creamy sauce! - Pan seared scallops*** So fresh and tender! - Seared Foie Gras*** Amazingly smooth! - Roast Maine Lobster*** Flavorful and tender! - Branzini*** Crispy outside, tender and moist inside! - Pork belly (in pork tenderloin dish)*** Perfect texture with a bit sweetness - duck hash (in duck breast dish)*** All the brunch places should learn from it! - Chocolate Soufflé with two sauces*** fluffy with the right amount of sweetness, the best possible way to finish dinner!

Gary Danko, you get my 500th review! 4.5 stars...not quiet perfect but close, and I did really enjoy our dining experience here. This was my second visit here (with about four years in between), and I am still a fan! My girl friend booked the private room for a group of us. The private room is quiet tight (the table seated 9 of us), but it was quiet and set up with nice flower arrangements. It is up an awkwardly angled staircase that makes coming down with heels interesting, but I guess you can label it was part of the charm. I had four courses...and a half (ended up ordering the soup and splitting it with my friend). I started with the fried egg with mushrooms and greens - very delicious and I only wish I could have it for breakfast at least once a week! The egg was not pan-fried, but deep fried with a perfect crust and an oozy middle. Next I had the sea bass with gnocchi. This dish was good, but not a wow-dish. I thought it was good but slightly under-salted. But as a side note, the scallops my husband ordered were giant and very tasty! I then split the corn soup with crab with my friend. I omitted the crab in my bowl since I am allergic to it, but the soup was delicious - sweet, and creamy but not over-the-top thick. Next I had the duck dish. It was well cooked and tender, but I did not favor the flavor profile. For my last course, I had the chocolate soufflé, which was well done. The soufflé and the vanilla and chocolate sauces that are poured into it were yummy. We also got a loaf of pumpkin cake (or bread?) to take home, and that's for tonight...! The service was great - attentive. I also had the strawberry margarita (okay, nothing fabulous) and we had a bottle of prosecco and I finished with a cup of decaf coffee, which was good. Gary Danko is worth the wait for your reservation...

Quality Service Value All in equal proportion. A wonderful experience for anyone that enjoys excellent food, combined with excellent service and value.

I can't believe it took me so long to dine at Gary Danko. After hearing countless praises and reading reviews, I had high expectations. For the most part, GD delivered. We did not have a reservation (our fault) so we were seated at the bar. Our servers were the also the bartenders so we had lovely service from Juan-Carlos and Jake. Our amuse bouche was pureed vegetables (peas? can't remember) but I remember it had chunks of dungeness crab in it. Always a hit, of course. I got the 3 course tasting menu. I ordered Sweet Corn Soup (Dungeness Crab, Roasted Red Pepper, Spiced Crème Fraîche, Bacon and a Chive Biscuitit), Scallops (Seared with Zucchini-Basil Purée, Beech Mushrooms, Melted Leeks and Sauce Maréchal) and Chocolate Praline Parfait (Bourbon Sauce and Salted Caramel Ice Cream). Every dish was well thought out and delicious. The food itself was 4.5 stars. Pacing was a little erratic, but that's because we were at the bar and Juan-Carlos and Jake were a little bit overwhelmed by the fully seated bar. Juan-Carlos was very patient and kept his cool when I pointed out that I didn't have silverware when they served our dessert. Next time I'll make reservations in advance for a table, I'm sure the experience will be a wee bit better.

This restaurant was superb. I love to try new food experiences but I tend to shy away from really expensive places just because 1. There is a plethora of moderately priced restaurants that hit all of my tummy's spots, and 2. The food I try never lives up to the hype. My godmother loves gourmet dining so I accompanied her; curious about the french-american cuisine she raved about. She told me to get a reservation in that place was a chore in itself but she knew somebody ; ). Upon entering we were welcomed by a friendly hostess and waited five minutes to be sat with a reservation . The restaurant was elegantly designed, kind of "Zen Chic," the seating was a little cramped with about two feet apart from the next table making it necessary to choose our conversation wisely. As I tuned into the restaurant I could tell it had a very internationally diverse crowd which was a plus for me. Our waiters were well informed on the very extensive and confusing menu. My godmother had to explain it to me even after our waiter gave us a five minute overview. You can choose between a 3, 4 or 5 course dinner. The menu looks like a cluster of items but each line is a meal that you can choose for a course. Bullet marks would have made it easier to understand for me at first glance but I am sure it would have taken from the elegant print. The food! Oh my...lets just say wow. There were some interesting amuse bouche(s?) brought to us to eat like a tiny pear soup with some sort of creme fraiche, and a sprinkle of bacon. You have to eat it collectively to experience the fireworks of flavors. The most interesting amuse bouche was a buckwheat pastry with creme fraiche, smoked salmon, and caviar. If I could eat it everyday...I would. I could go on and on, but I will end by saying. Whether you are celebrating a special something or are looking to splurge on a dining experience that will take you to culinary heights you've never reached before, OR you just want to be graced by a night of elegant service and ambiance give Gary Denko's a try. I am sure you will be pleased.

    Gary Danko, you get my 500th review!

    4.5 stars...not quiet perfect but close, and I did really enjoy our dining experience here.  This was my second visit here (with about four years in between), and I am still a fan!

    My girl friend booked the private room for a group of us.  The private room is quiet tight (the table seated 9 of us), but it was quiet and set up with nice flower arrangements.  It is up an awkwardly angled staircase that makes coming down with heels interesting, but I guess you can label it was part of the charm.

    I had four courses...and a half (ended up ordering the soup and splitting it with my friend).

    I started with the fried egg with mushrooms and greens - very delicious and I only wish I could have it for breakfast at least once a week!  The egg was not pan-fried, but deep fried with a perfect crust and an oozy middle.

    Next I had the sea bass with gnocchi.  This dish was good, but not a wow-dish.  I thought it was good but slightly under-salted.  But as a side note, the scallops my husband ordered were giant and very tasty!

    I then split the corn soup with crab with my friend.  I omitted the crab in my bowl since I am allergic to it, but the soup was delicious - sweet, and creamy but not over-the-top thick.

    Next I had the duck dish.  It was well cooked and tender, but I did not favor the flavor profile.  

    For my last course, I had the chocolate soufflé, which was well done.  The soufflé and the vanilla and chocolate sauces that are poured into it were yummy.  

    We also got a loaf of pumpkin cake (or bread?) to take home, and that's for tonight...!

    The service was great - attentive.  I also had the strawberry margarita (okay, nothing fabulous) and we had a bottle of prosecco and I finished with a cup of decaf coffee, which was good.

    Gary Danko is worth the wait for your reservation...

    My partner and I had dinner here on Monday and left feeling that it was a mediocre experience full of disappointments both small and large. The attention to detail that I would expect from a restaurant of this caliber simply was not there - or if it was, it was highly inconsistent. In general, we found the dishes uninspiring or downright poorly executed (with a few notable exceptions), the wait staff inconsistently attentive, and left feeling thoroughly unimpressed. High points that deserve mention are the madeira selection, the crab risotto, the scallops, and the cheese selection.

    Here's what failed to live up to expectations:
    -The asparagus appetizer just isn't very good
    -Course pacing was much too fast
    -The crusted tuna was bad. I sent it back due to tough fish and much too coarse crust. To their credit, waitstaff made this seamless and the scallop replacement was delicious.
    -When I ordered my second glass of wine, the server poured it (a different wine) into the same glass
    -Sharp knives were not provided with the quail, which was tender enough to do without, but it was definitely missed
    -The creme brulee trio tasted excellent, but were mis-identified by staff and the accompanying cookies were 1) unrelated to the flavors of the dessert 2) not good cookies 3) not described by staff and 4) detracted significantly from the overall dish
    -When I ordered coffee, I had to wait five minutes before I could get someone's attention that coffee service had not been brought with my espresso in order to add a sugar cube
    -The dessert spoons were so big I had trouble fitting them into my mouth. I would not add this if it had not been a major annoyance and detraction from the dishes.
    -Several times, water refilling at the table forced me back from my plate mid-bite
    -Dirty dishes were very inconsistently cleared (see reused wine glass)

    I have very high standards for a restaurant such as this. My partner and I walked in excited to be wowed by perfect cuisine and excellent service, and left feeling as though we had just wasted $450. I was incredibly disappointed to find myself sending a dish back.

    Consider choosing somewhere else for your fine dining experience.

    - Quail Stuffed with Foie Gras, Mushroom and Quinoa, Braised Artichokes, Peas, Prosciutto and Olive Butter. ( Quail and Fioe Gras was scrumptious!)

    - Seared Filet of Beef with Potatoes Panadera, Swiss Chard, Cassis Glazed Shallots and Bordelaise Butter. (definitely melt in my mouth)

    - Coriander, Black Pepper and Rosemary Crusted Tuna with Piperade, Summer Beans and Anchovy Essence. ( rosemary and coriander was a good blend for the tuna)

    - Seared Sea Scallops with Asparagus-Pea Purée, Pickled Radish, Spring Onions and Sauce Maréchal. ( scallops was seared to perfection!)

    - Lobster Salad with Asian Pear, Mango, Avocado, Cashews and Lime Cilantro Rémoulade. ( Refreshing and light texture, perfect for appetizer)

    - Lemon Soufflé Cake with Créme Frache Panna Cotta and Raspberry Sorbet.

    - Warm Louisiana Butter Cake with Roasted Apricots, Elderberry Sauce and Vanilla Bean Ice Cream. ( Best dessert bread pudding)

    - Squash soup ( I love squash soup in general)

    Each and every entrees was unique and flavorful. Perfect portion size and excellent service at its finest. One of my favorite fine dining places to go to in SF.
